First, draw a sketch. We can label the \(F\) axis by adding integer multiples of 0.5 to 2.1. We know to shade the right because high values of \(F\) satisfy the condition \(F>f\) (regardless of the exact value of \(f\)). We donâ€™t know exactly where to place the boundary, but we know the right area is 0.83.


We know how to find the left area. \[\begin{aligned} P(F<f) &= 1-P(F>f) \\ &= 1-0.83 \\ &= 0.17 \end{aligned}\]


As an intermediate step, we find \(z\) such that \(P(Z<z)=0.17\).

By using the \(z\) table we can determine \(z\).

\(z\) \(P(Z<z)\)
-0.98 0.1635
-0.97 0.166
-0.96 0.1685
-0.95 0.1711
-0.94 0.1736
-0.97 0.1762

Either -0.96 or -0.95 is a good estimation of \(z\), and either value will lead you to an acceptable answer. Using other tools, a more accurate value can be found. I will show the work with a more accurate value. \[z=-0.9542\]

We now convert the \(z\) score into a \(f\) score. \[\begin{aligned} f &= \mu+z\sigma \\ &= 2.1+(-0.9542)(0.5) \\ &= 1.623 \end{aligned}\]

We can also visualize this with a spinner.


The tolerance for an acceptable answer was \(\pm 0.1\) from 1.6229174. So, anything between 1.5229174 and 1.7229174 was accepted.
